statement: The presence of specific PAHs (Fluoranthene and Pyrene) in Antarctic meteorites (ALH 83100, LON 94101, LEW 85311) suggests a common formation environment or source for these organic compounds in the early solar system before incorporation into distinct meteorite parent bodies.  The detection of these compounds indicates that these molecules can survive the processes of meteorite formation and delivery to Earth.
comments: This is mostly consistent with the literature, but the presence of these molecules isn't necessarily evidence that they formed in the nebula - they could have formed through common reaction pathways within the asteroid parent bodies
key_datapoints: Fluoranthene (C16H10) and Pyrene (C16H10) are detected in ALH 83100, LON 94101, and LEW 85311 (ID 12 and 13)

statement: The co-occurrence of Naphthalene (C10H8) and 2-Methyl naphthalene (C11H10) in Orgueil, ALH 83100, LON 94101, Murchison, Jbilet Winselwan, and LEW 85311 indicates that these PAHs are either co-synthesized or that the methylation of naphthalene is a common diagenetic process occurring on the parent bodies of these meteorites. The presence of both compounds in both biotic and abiotic samples suggests that the presence of these two compounds is not a good indicator of life.
comments: A very small comment, but diagenesis refers to processes that occur when sediments are converted into sedimentary rocks, so I think "alteration" would be a better term
key_datapoints: Naphthalene (C10H8) and 2-Methyl naphthalene (C11H10) presence in Orgueil, ALH 83100, LON 94101, Aguas Zarcas, Murchison, Jbilet Winselwan, LEW 85311, Green River Shale soil, and Lignite Soil (ID 1 and 2)

statement: The presence of 1,2,4-Trithiolane (C2H4S3) in Aguas Zarcas and LEW 85311 suggests that there was low-temperature aqueous alteration occurring on the parent asteroids that led to the formation of these specific organosulfur compounds. This further suggests that the original organic make-up of the parent bodies for Aguas Zarcas and LEW 85311 may be similar.
comments: The presence of these compounds doesn't mean that they formed through low-temperature aqueous processes; we need more information about the parent body histories
key_datapoints: 1,2,4-Trithiolane (C2H4S3) is detected in Aguas Zarcas and LEW 85311 (ID 27)

statement: Aqueous alteration on carbonaceous chondrite parent bodies may preferentially incorporate smaller, more soluble aromatic compounds like naphthalene, methylindan, and biphenyl into the aqueously altered regions, leading to their increased presence in aqueously altered meteorites like Orgueil, ALH 83100, LON 94101, and LEW 85311.  This is evidenced by those meteorites showing the common presence of naphthalene (ID 1), 2-Methyl naphthalene (ID 2),  1-Methyl naphthalene (ID 8), Indane (ID 11) and Biphenyl (ID 43).
key_datapoints: Naphthalene (ID 1), 2-Methyl naphthalene (ID 2), 1-Methyl naphthalene (ID 8), Indane (ID 11), Biphenyl (ID 43), Orgueil, ALH 83100, LON 94101, LEW 85311

statement: Terrestrial soils (Iceland, Atacama, GSFC, Utah) show unique organic compounds, including possible terpenes or sesquiterpenes, due to their unique environments and biomes, but these compounds are not prevalent in the meteorite samples.
comments: This is an observation, not a hypothesis
key_datapoints: Possible terpene or sesquiterpene (IDs 4, 17, 18), Polysubstituted alkylbenzene with formula C12H18 (ID 5), Tetrame thylindene (ID 20), Iceland Soil, Atacama, Utah soil Soil, GSFC soil Soil, Murchison Soil

statement: The presence of specific compounds such as Dichlorobenzene and a Bicyclo derivative in Murchison and Orgueil, which are absent from other samples, indicates the distinctiveness of the organic inventory of these two meteorites and the potential for unique formation pathways or source materials.
key_datapoints: Dichlorobenzene (ID 29), Bicyclo[2.2.1]heptan-2-one, 1,7,7-trimethyl-, (1S)- (ID 30), Orgueil, Murchison

statement: The absence of toluene (C7H8) in Aguas Zarcas and Jbilet Winselwan, while present in the other carbonaceous chondrites (ALH 83100, LON 94101, Murchison, and LEW 85311) indicates that aqueous or thermal alteration processes might have altered or removed the compound, or that original source material for these meteorites was different. Furthermore, the presence of Toluene might suggest formation at lower temperatures, thus not requiring high energy input.
comments: The presence of toluene in only some meteorites could also indicate that it only formed in some asteroids. There is also no evidence that toluene formed through low-temperature processes; we need more information about the parent body histories
key_datapoints: Toluene (C7H8) is present in ALH 83100, LON 94101, Murchison, and LEW 85311 but absent in Aguas Zarcas and Jbilet Winselwan.

statement: The co-occurrence of dibenzo thiophene (C12H8S),  Trimethyl naphthalene (C13H14), 1H-Phenalen-1-one or 9H-Fluoren-9-one (C13H8O)  and  Dimethylpyrene (C18H14) in Orgueil and LEW 85311, while not detected in other meteorites, suggests that these sulfur and oxygen containing compounds may be formed in the same conditions, potentially during aqueous alteration. The absence in other samples can be explained by: 1) their removal by subsequent higher degrees of aqueous alteration, or 2) a requirement for specific elemental composition to be present.
comments: The first part of the hypothesis is accurate, but the absence of these compounds doesn't suggest that they were removed through aqueous alteration or that specific elements are required for these compounds to form - differing conditions is more likely. Sulfur and oxygen are present in all carbonaceous chondrites
key_datapoints: Dibenzo thiophene (C12H8S),  Trimethyl naphthalene (C13H14), 1H-Phenalen-1-one or 9H-Fluoren-9-one (C13H8O)  and  Dimethylpyrene (C18H14) are present in Orgueil and LEW 85311.

statement: The presence of the same possible terpene or sesquiterpene (low confidence) in both Iceland Soil and Rio Tinto Soil suggests convergent production pathways for these molecules under disparate environmental conditions (cold and volcanic vs. acidic and high-iron). This suggests that these abiotic processes are highly robust and not dependent on specific conditions.
comments: These molecules are produced by biology, not abiotic processes
key_datapoints: Possible terpene or sesquiterpene (low confidence) is found in both Iceland Soil and Rio Tinto Soil.

statement: The detection of the same unknown (m/z 154.0) in both Green River Shale soil and Lignite Soil may suggest a shared diagenetic pathway transforming precursor molecules into this unknown over long periods of time. The presence of this unknown could be an indicator for the presence of mature organic matter.
key_datapoints: An unknown with m/z 154.0 is present in both Green River Shale soil and Lignite Soil.

statement: The co-occurrence of 1,2,4-Trithiolane with Naphthalene, 2-Methyl naphthalene, 1-Methyl naphthalene, Indane, Fluoranthene, and Pyrene in Aguas Zarcas, LEW 85311, and Orgueil suggests that sulfur-containing compounds such as 1,2,4-Trithiolane are also incorporated during aqueous alteration of the meteorites in addition to the lighter carbon compounds.
comments: The presence of these compounds doesn't necessarily indicate that they formed through aqueous alteration, and I'm not sure the co-occurance of these compounds indicates a relationship
key_datapoints: 1,2,4-Trithiolane (ID 27), Naphthalene, 2-Methyl naphthalene, 1-Methyl naphthalene, Indane, Fluoranthene, Pyrene, Aguas Zarcas, LEW 85311, Orgueil

statement: The presence of specific compounds like Dimethyl cyclohexane (C8H16), Methylindan (C10H12), and 1,2,3,4-tetrahydro phenanthrene (C14H14) in Antarctic meteorites (ALH 83100, LON 94101, LEW 85311) suggests that even under extreme environmental conditions, certain cyclic aliphatic and aromatic hydrocarbons can be preserved over long periods. This could be due to their inherent stability or presence within protective mineral matrices.
comments: Sort of; these compounds do have high preservation potential, but cold conditions are generally very good for preserving organics while hot/acidic/oxidizing/wet conditions would be considered more extreme. The temperature in space is also much colder than on Antarctica
key_datapoints: Dimethyl cyclohexane (C8H16), Methylindan (C10H12), 1,2,3,4-tetrahydro phenanthrene (C14H14), ALH 83100, LON 94101, LEW 85311

statement: The co-occurrence of Naphthalene (C10H8), 2-Methyl naphthalene (C11H10), 1-Methyl naphthalene (C11H10), Pyrene (C16H10), and Fluoranthene (C16H10) in both the Orgueil meteorite (CI1) and the studied Antarctic meteorites (ALH 83100, LON 94101, LEW 85311) indicates a shared formation environment or source material within the early solar system. It also suggests that aqueous alteration was not strong enough to remove these compounds.
comments: The first part is accurate, but aqueous alteration doesn't necessarily remove PAHs, and Orgueil and ALH 83100 are the most aqueously altered meteorites we looked at
key_datapoints: Naphthalene (C10H8), 2-Methyl naphthalene (C11H10), 1-Methyl naphthalene (C11H10), Pyrene (C16H10), Fluoranthene (C16H10), Orgueil, ALH 83100, LON 94101, LEW 85311

statement: The detection of similar compounds (Dimethyl cyclohexane, Possible terpene or sesquiterpene) in Iceland Soil, Atacama Desert soil, and GSFC soil suggests a common origin and/or similar formation pathways for specific organic compounds in geologically diverse soils. If such compounds were found on another planetary body, they would not be strong biosignatures.
comments: The first part of the hypothesis is accurate, but since these compounds are only produced by biology and only found in terrestrial samples, they would be strong biosignatures
key_datapoints: Dimethyl cyclohexane (C8H16), Possible terpene or sesquiterpene, Iceland Soil, Atacama Desert soil, GSFC soil

statement: The detection of toluene, methylnaphthalenes, acenaphthene, dibenzothiophene, and trimethylnaphthalene in Orgueil and LEW 85311 suggests a common origin or similar formation pathways for these PAHs in both samples. The presence of these compounds suggests that these PAHs are relatively stable and can be preserved under different environmental conditions.
key_datapoints: Toluene, Methylnaphthalenes, Acenaphthene, Dibenzo thiophene, Trimethyl naphthalene, Orgueil, LEW 85311

statement: The detection of 1,2,4-Trithiolane (C2H4S3) in Aguas Zarcas and LEW 85311, both CM2 chondrites, suggests similar parent body processes were present in the formation and evolution. The presence of this sulfur compound can be correlated with aqueous alteration.
comments: The first part of the hypothesis is accurate, but the presence of these compounds doesn't necessarily indicate that it is correlated with aqueous alteration
key_datapoints: 1,2,4-Trithiolane (C2H4S3), Aguas Zarcas, LEW 85311

statement: The presence of various compounds only in the biotic samples, such as Ergost-14-ene, (5?)- (C28H48) in Lignite Soil and Murchison Soil, suggests that these compounds are potential indicators of biology. The presence of these compounds and their absence from the abiotic samples in the dataset could be used as a benchmark for future space exploration missions.
key_datapoints: Ergost-14-ene, (5?)- (C28H48), Lignite Soil, Murchison Soil

statement: Aqueous alteration on carbonaceous chondrite parent bodies preferentially incorporates smaller PAHs (e.g., Naphthalene, Toluene) into the meteorite, while depleting the larger PAHs, as those PAHs are more likely to undergo aqueous reactions and be removed. This is supported by the observation that Orgueil, a highly aqueously altered meteorite, contains Naphthalene and Toluene, but lacks Fluoranthene and Pyrene.
comments: This isn't accurate; aqueous alteration preferentially removes small PAHs, which are more water-soluble compared to water-insoluble large PAHs
key_datapoints: Orgueil contains Naphthalene (ID 1) and Toluene (ID 7), but lacks Fluoranthene and Pyrene (both ID 12 and 13).

statement: The presence of Dimethyl Cyclohexane (C8H16) specifically in LEW 85311 and EET 96029 suggests that this compound may be a product of a specific alteration pathway that these Antarctic CM2 meteorites experienced, distinct from other CM2 meteorites. This could be due to unique terrestrial alteration processes related to the Antarctic environment, or it could be due to a unique aqueous alteration environment that has been altered or erased in other meteorites.
comments: Mostly accurate, but the presence of these compounds doesn’t necessarily indicate they were formed through aqueous proceesses
key_datapoints: Dimethyl cyclohexane (ID 25) is only found in LEW 85311 and EET 96029.

statement: The co-occurrence of Fluoranthene (ID 12) or Pyrene (ID 13) and 1,2,4-Trithiolane (C2H4S3, ID 27) in ALH 83100 and LEW 85311 suggests that this sulfur-containing compound may be a product of aqueous alteration of fluoranthene and pyrene.
comments: Correlation does not equal causation; there are no known pathways for forming 1,2,4-trithiolane from fluoranthene or pyrene
key_datapoints: 1,2,4-Trithiolane (ID 27) is present in ALH 83100 and LEW 85311 which also contain Fluoranthene (ID 12) or Pyrene (ID 13).

statement: The co-occurrence of multiple unknown compounds in Iceland Soil, Atacama, and GSFC soil suggests that these soils share similar depositional environments and/or source material.  This is based on the fact that they all contain ID 4, 5, and 10, which are uncharacterized species.
key_datapoints: ID 4, 5, and 10 occur in Iceland Soil, Atacama, and GSFC soil.

statement: The high presence of oxygen-containing PAHs in Ivuna suggests parent body aqueous alteration involved oxidation processes that enriched oxygen-containing PAHs relative to standard PAHs. This is supported by the limited presence of oxygen-containing PAHs in other samples, suggesting aqueous alteration was either less prominent, or different in nature.
comments: We didn't analyze an Ivuna meteorite sample
key_datapoints: Ivuna, C14H10O, C16H10O

statement: The detection of 1,2,4-Trithiolane in Aguas Zarcas and LEW 85311, but the absence of dimethyl cyclohexane, indicates that there were unique sulfurization processes on their parent body. The presence of the specific trithiolane indicates that sulfurization was selective and that there were specific conditions on the parent bodies to form it. The high concentration of dimethyl cyclohexane in LEW 85311 and EET 96029 compared to the other meteorites suggests a distinct formation or preservation environment of small, volatile alicyclics on their parent body.
comments: Mostly accurate, but I don't think there's any relationship between 1,2,4-trithiolane and dimethylcyclohexane. The last 2 statements are accurate
key_datapoints: 1,2,4-Trithiolane, Dimethyl cyclohexane, Aguas Zarcas, LEW 85311, EET 96029

statement: The presence of toluene and 1-methyl naphthalene in the Orgueil and Murchison meteorites, and the absence of indane, fluoranthene, pyrene, and dibenzo thiophene, is indicative of high levels of aqueous alteration on the parent body. The higher water solubility of toluene and 1-methyl naphthalene would allow these compounds to be easily mobilized and detected, while the other compounds, due to their lower solubility, would be less prominent.
comments: Mostly accurate, but the absence of certain larger PAHs doesn't necessarily have anything to do with aqueous alteration, especially because insolubility in water means that they are less likely to be removed
key_datapoints: Orgueil, Murchison, Toluene, 1-Methyl naphthalene, Indane, Fluoranthene, Pyrene, Dibenzo thiophene

statement: The co-occurrence of acenaphthene, dimethyl pyrene and polysubstituted alkylnaphthalene in ALH 83100 and LEW 85311 suggests a shared petrogenesis or parent body fluid alteration history where these compounds were produced together. The presence of indane, fluoranthene, pyrene, and dibenzo thiophene in these samples, but absence in the other carbonaceous chondrites suggests unique formation conditions.
key_datapoints: ALH 83100, LEW 85311, Acenaphthene, Dimethylpyrene, Polysubstituted alkylnaphthalene, Indane, Fluoranthene, Pyrene, Dibenzo thiophene

statement: Aqueous alteration on carbonaceous chondrite parent bodies leads to the degradation of larger PAHs into smaller, more volatile compounds, which are then lost to space or become localized in regions of low aqueous activity. The increase in smaller compounds results in lower m/z distributions in HR-L2MS analysis.
comments: We didn't perform HR-L2MS analyses or analyze any of the meteorites listed in the key datapoints column
key_datapoints: Chwichiya 002 (C3.00u): Dominance of C14H10, lack of larger PAHs. Ivuna (CI1) and NWA 12328 (CM1): Dominance of larger PAHs, low signal of smaller PAHs. See also the general trend of increased smaller PAH size with decreasing aqueous alteration.

statement: Hydrothermal activity, through Fischer-Tropsch type reactions, produces a wide range of aliphatic and aromatic hydrocarbons and their derivatives, but has a limited effect on the production of specific biomarkers (such as the long chains of carbon structures).
comments: This is true, but because Fischer-Tropsch type reactions are abiotic, they can't produce biomarkers
key_datapoints: High abundance of aliphatic hydrocarbons in Green River Shale soil and Lignite soil in contrast to smaller peaks from PAH signals.

statement: The detection of oxygenated PAHs in the most aqueously altered meteorites indicates oxidative stress, which is consistent with the idea that oxidation is one of the most important factors in the degradation of organic matter in CCs.
comments: We didn't analyze Ivuna or NWA 12328
key_datapoints: Ivuna (CI1) and NWA 12328 (CM1) higher oxygenated PAHs peaks compared to other samples.

statement: The presence of a high proportion of compounds with positive mass defects in organic-rich soils indicates the presence of heteroatoms, in particular nitrogen and oxygen, suggesting that these compounds are different from the PAHs found in meteorites.
key_datapoints: Most of the peaks detected in Iceland soil, Rio Tinto Soil, GSFC soil Soil, and Utah Soil have positive mass defects, while the majority of the peaks detected in meteorites are hydrocarbon PAHs.

statement: In CM2 chondrites, the degree of aqueous alteration correlates with the ratio of 1-Methyl naphthalene to 2-Methyl naphthalene, serving as a potential proxy for the extent of parent body processing. Specifically, a lower 1-Methyl naphthalene to 2-Methyl naphthalene ratio indicates higher degree of aqueous alteration.

statement: The presence of Indane (C9H10) in ALH 83100, LON 94101, and LEW 85311, suggests a unique formation pathway or source specific to the Antarctic CM chondrites that is distinct from the formation environment of Orgueil and other CM chondrites.

I'll rank the hypothesis under the assumption that "Antarctic CM chondrites" means "these 3 CM chondrites"

statement: The presence of alkylated naphthalenes in both the biotic Green River Shale soil and the abiotic carbonaceous chondrites indicates that alkylation processes are not unique to biotic environments and may be influenced by abiotic factors such as aqueous alteration.

statement: The presence of toluene (C7H8) and indane (C9H10) in Antarctic meteorites (ALH 83100, LON 94101, and LEW 85311) suggests a pre-solar origin where these simple aromatics formed in the interstellar medium and were incorporated into the meteorite parent body during its formation. The detection of these compounds, which are not as readily linked to biological processes, provides evidence of the survival of pre-solar material within these meteorites.
comments: The presence of these compounds doesn't necessarily indicate that they formed in the interstellar medium, as opposed to secondary processing in the parent body

statement: The co-occurrence of naphthalene (C10H8) and 2-methylnaphthalene (C11H10) in both Orgueil and the Antarctic meteorites (ALH 83100, LON 94101, and LEW 85311), suggests a common formation pathway on the meteorite parent body, likely involving the low-temperature gas-phase reaction of phenyl radicals with vinylacetylene as described by Parker et al. This contrasts with the high-temperature combustion synthesis of PAHs in terrestrial environments.

statement: The absence of fluoranthene (C16H10) and pyrene (C16H10) in the most aqueously altered meteorite, Aguas Zarcas, suggests that aqueous alteration processes on meteorite parent bodies may selectively degrade larger PAHs, leading to a relative enrichment of smaller PAHs. The presence of naphthalene in Aguas Zarcas, however, implies that it is more resistant to this degradation.
comments: ALH 83100 and Orgeuil are the most aqueously altered meteorites we looked at. The absence of fluoranthene and pyrene also is probably because they didn't form, not that they were degraded

statement: The identification of distinct, low-confidence terpene or sesquiterpene-like compounds (ID 4, ID 17, ID 18) uniquely within the Iceland Soil, Atacama, and GSFC soil samples implies the presence of unique, low-abundance, and high-volatility biological compounds. statement: The detection of toluene, dimethyl cyclohexane, methylindan, acenaphthene, and trimethyl naphthalene in the carbonaceous chondrites (Orgueil, ALH 83100, LEW 85311, LON 94101, Aguas Zarcas, Jbilet Winselwan, Murchison, and EET 96029) suggests that these volatile, low-molecular-weight aromatic and cycloaliphatic hydrocarbons are common products of abiotic organic synthesis within meteorite parent bodies. These compounds may represent a baseline of organic molecules to which further complexification can occur. This contrasts with the soils, which lack consistent detection of these compounds.

statement: The presence of fluoranthene and pyrene, along with alkylated naphthalenes, in ALH 83100, LON 94101, and LEW 85311, suggests that these polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs) and their alkylated derivatives were synthesized during the formation and aqueous alteration of the parent asteroids. The co-occurrence of these PAHs may point to a shared origin and/or similar formation conditions within the asteroid's environment.

statement: The identification of compounds (ID 30 & 31), suggestive of terpenes (Bicyclo[2.2.1]heptan-2-one, 1,7,7-trimethyl-, (1S)-) and cymene (o-Cymene), only in Murchison and Orgueil suggests these meteorites experienced a unique form of parent body processing not shared by the Antarctic meteorites. This suggests localized regions on the parent bodies experienced different alteration processes, and the specific alteration history was different than the Antarctic meteorites in this study.
key_datapoints: Bicyclo[2.2.1]heptan-2-one, 1,7,7-trimethyl-, (1S)- (ID 30), o-Cymene (ID 31), Murchison, Orgueil
